-
-### Core concept
-Ch 1 establishes two load-bearing definitions: (a) **architecture** = "an abstract description of the entities of a system and the relationship between those entities" (line 399); in systems built by humans, "this architecture can be represented as a set of decisions." (b) The **central assertion** of the book: "early decisions can be analyzed and treated. … structured creativity is better than unstructured creativity" (line 409). These two sentences anchor the entire Crawley method — architecture as a *decision object*, not a drawing, and the early (pre-detailed-design) decisions as the leverage point.
-
-### Key heuristics / operators / formulas
-- **The first-10-decisions rule** (line 606, set up in Ch 1 and formalized in Ch 14): the first ~10 architectural decisions determine the majority of performance and cost.
-- **Good-architecture checklist** (line 389): well-architected systems "meet stakeholder needs and deliver value," "integrate easily, evolve flexibly, and operate simply and reliably."
-- **Architect deliverables skeleton** (lines 435–449): use system thinking; analyze/critique existing architecture; identify architectural vs. non-architectural decisions; create new architecture; place architecture in competitive context; drive ambiguity from upstream; create concept (internal function + form); manage evolution of complexity; develop guiding principles.
-- **Principle/Method/Tool hierarchy** (line 450): *Principles* are long-enduring truths (always or nearly always valid); *Methods* are organized procedures (usually or often valid); *Tools* are contemporary facilitators (sometimes valid). c1v KB-1 should mirror this three-tier structure when labeling its own content.
-
-### Patcher-ready seed (200–500 words)
-System architecture, per Crawley Ch 1, is "an abstract description of the entities of a system and the relationship between those entities," and "in systems built by humans, this architecture can be represented as a set of decisions." KB-1 must therefore scope a project as a *decision object* from the first interaction — the c1v intake phase is architecturally identical to what Crawley calls "driving ambiguity from the upstream process" (Ch 9). The advantages of good architecture that Ch 1 enumerates are: the system meets stakeholder needs and delivers value; it integrates easily, evolves flexibly, and operates simply and reliably. Ch 1's worked failure case is NPOESS (lines 413–423): a 1994 merged weather-satellite program that absorbed every instrument capability from both parent programs without re-deriving a coherent system concept, trapping architectural performance "in an unreachable corner of its envelope" (VIIRS was to do three instruments' work at less mass/volume than one). The program was canceled in 2010 at $8.5B over its $6.5B baseline. Ch 1's paired success heuristic, from the 1962 Apollo Lunar Orbit Rendezvous decision (line 379), is that a *single early architectural decision*, made before the majority of staff is hired and before contracts are awarded, can "eliminate many possible designs" and give design teams a stable starting point. KB-1 scoping therefore has two explicit deliverables: (1) identify the one-or-few early decisions that carry this level of leverage, and (2) refuse to treat architecture as downstream-of-design. Ch 1 also draws the book's own "principles / methods / tools" distinction (line 450): principles are enduring truths, methods are organized procedures, tools are contemporary facilitators — a labeling convention KB-1 should adopt verbatim for its own content, so every c1v utterance can be tagged with its epistemic status. Ch 1 closes by framing the four parts of the book as the canonical pipeline: Part 1 = system thinking; Part 2 = analysis (reverse-engineer existing architectures); Part 3 = synthesis (create new architectures); Part 4 = architecture as decisions.
