-## Ch 3 — Thinking about Complex Systems [FILLED 2026-04-24]
-
-**Source:** markdown lines 1055–1334 / pdf pages ~49–64.
-**Target KB:** _shared.
-**Existing in-tree work:** findings.md §3.4 already authors ~180 words on OPM; this section extends to §3.3 decomposition, §3.4 logical relationships, §3.5 reasoning.
-
-### Core concept
-Ch 3 is the toolkit chapter that lifts the Ch 2 four-task method to apply to *complex* systems (many entities, highly interrelated). Definition: "a complex system has many elements or entities that are highly interrelated, interconnected, or interwoven" (Box 3.1, line 1075). The architect's job is to "build systems of the necessary level of complexity that are not complicated" (line 1089) — i.e., invest in complexity as needed but keep *apparent* complexity below the human comprehension ceiling.
-
-### Key heuristics / operators / formulas
-- **Simple / Medium / Complex taxonomy** (lines 1164–1180): simple = one-level decomposition with ≤7±2 atomic parts; medium = two-level with ≤(7±2)² ≈ 81 entities; complex = two-level with sub-abstractions (going deeper implies up to 729 entities, exceeds human capacity).
-- **Level 0 / Level 1 / Level 2 convention** (line 1180): standard depth convention used throughout the book.
-- **Hierarchy causes** (line 1141): more scope, more importance/performance, more responsibility.
-- **Atomic part test** (line 1184): mechanical — "call it a part when you can't take it apart"; informational — "call it a part if it loses meaning when you take it apart."
-- **Special Logical Relationships** (§3.4, lines 1190–1214): (a) **class/instance** — class = general features, instance = specific occurrence (VIN of a Ford Explorer). (b) **specialization/generalization** — akin to inheritance in OO programming (House → Colonial/Victorian/modern). (c) **recursion** — self-similar use (a Node class whose Neighbors attribute is an array of Nodes).
-- **Reasoning approaches** (§3.5, lines 1216–1234): (a) **top-down** (V-model left side), (b) **bottom-up**, (c) **outer-in** (meeting in the middle), (d) **middle-out** (standard for truly complex systems, reasoning one or two levels up/down from an arbitrary starting point), (e) **zigzagging** (Nam Suh's axiomatic-design term) — alternate between form and function domains.
-- **Representation choice** (§3.6): OPM (integrated model, single diagram) vs. SysML (9 views). Crawley uses OPM primarily, SysML as reference.
-
-### Patcher-ready seed (200–500 words)
-Ch 3 equips the architect with the four levers for keeping a complex system comprehensible while preserving its essential complexity: **decomposition**, **hierarchy**, **special logical relationships**, and **representation**. Decomposition breaks an entity into smaller pieces and is "one of the most powerful tools in our toolset for dealing with complexity" (line 1129) — but the hard problem is integration, not decomposition: recombining decomposed entities brings emergence back into play, and poorly chosen decomposition boundaries cause integration to fail. Hierarchy ranks entities into layers based on scope, importance, or responsibility (line 1141). Hierarchic decomposition combines the two: a multilevel breakdown that aligns with the human 7±2 cognitive limit. Crawley's simple/medium/complex classification (line 1164) bounds modeling depth — simple = one level with ≤9 atomic parts, medium = two levels with ≤81, complex = two levels but the second level still contains abstractions (not atomic). No one draws a three-level diagram because level 3 blows past 729 entities. The Level 0 / Level 1 / Level 2 convention (line 1180) is used throughout the book. Special logical relationships (§3.4) provide three extra primitives beyond entity+relationship: **class/instance** (a class describes general features; an instance is a specific occurrence — Ford Explorer model vs. a specific VIN), **specialization/generalization** (general House specializes to Colonial, Victorian, modern — structurally identical to OO inheritance), and **recursion** (a Node whose Neighbors attribute contains Nodes). Reasoning through complex systems (§3.5) supports four directions: top-down (goal-first, V-model left side), bottom-up (capability-first, predict emergence upward), outer-in (meet in the middle), and middle-out (start at an arbitrary hierarchy point, reason 1–2 levels up or down). Real-world analysis is always iterative, and the architect **zigzags** (Suh's term) between form and function domains — work in one as long as practical, then switch. Representation (§3.6) splits into integrated-model tools (OPM — single diagram, objects + processes + relationships) and multi-view tools (SysML — 9 diagram types, block-definition/internal-block for structure, activity/state-machine/use-case/sequence for behavior, parametric + requirements added). Crawley chooses OPM as primary with SysML references — this is c1v's warrant to do the same in KB-shared.
