-## Ch 4 — Form [FILLED 2026-04-24]
-
-**Source:** markdown lines 1383–1988 / pdf pages ~67–95.
-**Target KB:** 5-form-function.
-**Existing in-tree work:** `GLOSSARY-crawley.md` at `.../5-form-function-mapping/` likely already covers Box 4.1 form definition — patcher should cross-reference before expanding.
-
-### Core concept
-Form is "the physical or informational embodiment of a system that exists (or has the potential to exist) and is instrumental in the execution of function" (Box 4.1, summarized at line 1397). Form is what the system IS. It exists prior to function execution. Form decomposes into objects and structure (formal relationships).
-
-### Key heuristics / operators / formulas
-- **Two tests for form** (line 1397): (1) it exists; (2) it is instrumental in executing function.
-- **Three types of formal relationships** (§4.4, lines 1810–1817): (a) **spatial/topological** — where things are (above/below, within, aligned, adjacent, near/far); (b) **connectivity** — what is connected/linked/joined to what (the carrier of functional interactions); (c) **intangible** — address, sequence, membership, ownership, human relationships.
-- **Structure definition** (Box 4.4, line 1613): "relationships between objects of form that have the potential for stable, unconditional existence for some duration of time and may be instrumental in the execution of functional interactions."
-- **OPM graphical convention** (line 1669): single-headed labeled arrow between objects; direction arbitrary; label describes relationship.
-- **DSM representation** (Box 4.6, line 1704): N×N matrix; convention — read down column to row; entries "flow" from column heading to row heading. For *structure* entries the matrix is symmetric (since structure has no causality).
-- **Procedure for identifying relationships** (line 1639): examine each pairwise set of objects and ask "is this spatial/topological (or connectivity) relationship key to some important functional interaction or to the successful emergence of function and performance?"
-- **Principle of Dualism** (Box 4.7, line 1888): all built systems exist simultaneously in physical and informational domains. Informational form must always be encoded in physical form (poems in print; thoughts in neural patterns; DVDs in optical markings).
-- **Accompanying systems + whole product system + use context** (§4.5, lines 1822–1857): **whole product system** = product/system + accompanying systems (necessary for value delivery); **use context** = objects normally present during operation but not necessary for value; architect is "accountable two levels out in context, two levels down in decomposition."
-- **Software form** (§4.6, lines 1866–1977): code IS form (exists prior to execution, interpretable as instructions). Spatial/topological structure = sequence + containment (which lines are inside which loops). Connectivity structure = shared variables.
-
-### Patcher-ready seed (200–500 words)
-Crawley Ch 4 defines form as what the system IS — the physical or informational embodiment that exists (or could exist) and is instrumental in executing function. Every form passes two tests: it exists, and it carries function. Form decomposes into two components: **objects** (the elements of form, the parts/modules/routines), and **structure** (the set of formal relationships between those objects). Structure is "the set of relationships that exist and do not require change, exchange, or anything that happens along a timeline" (line 1619). Box 4.1 establishes form as the static, perseverant side of the system — what remains when the system is not operating. Ch 4's procedural contribution is a taxonomy of formal relationships (§4.4): **spatial/topological** (location, placement — above/below/within/adjacent/aligned — matters because it may enable "ballistic" interactions or inform performance); **connectivity** (what is connected to what — the enabler of most functional interactions, because transfers require carriers: wires carry current, arteries carry blood, shared addresses carry data); **intangible** (address, sequence, membership, ownership, human bonds — static but changeable). Crawley represents form two ways, always equivalently: **OPM graphs** (objects as boxes, relationships as labeled single-headed arrows) and **Design Structure Matrices** (N×N, read-down-the-column-to-the-row; symmetric for structure because structure has no causality). The identification procedure is uniform: "examine each pairwise set of objects and ask: is this relationship key to some important functional interaction or to the successful emergence of function and performance?" (line 1639). This is the filter that prevents over-specification. Ch 4 §4.5 introduces the three-layer context model the architect must always hold: **product/system** (what the architect owns), **whole product system** (product + accompanying systems necessary for value — the pump plus hoses, mount, power, operator), **use context** (what is present during operation but optional — the physical room, the climate, the nearby infrastructure). Architects are "accountable two levels out in context and two levels down in decomposition." Ch 4 §4.6 extends everything to software (Principle of Dualism, Box 4.7): code IS form — it exists prior to execution, is instrumental when interpreted as instructions. Software's spatial/topological structure is sequence + containment (which lines are inside which loops — think indentation), and its connectivity structure is shared variables. Every architectural concept in Ch 4 applies to software unchanged.
