-
-### Core concept
-Ch 6 defines system architecture (Box 6.1, line 2535): "the embodiment of concept, the allocation of physical/informational function to the elements of form, and the definition of relationships among the elements and with the surrounding context." Architecture is not an independent attribute — it is the **mapping** between form and function (Figure 6.1).
-
-### Key heuristics / operators / formulas
-- **Principle of Value and Architecture** (Box 6.2, line 2549): "Value is benefit at cost. Architecture is function enabled by form. … developing good architectures (desired function for minimal form) will be nearly synonymous with the delivery of value." Form attracts cost (lean axiom); function emerges benefit.
-- **Non-1:1 mapping taxonomy** (Figure 6.5, lines 2620–2642): (a) **no instrument** (melting — what does the melting? must be a missing instrument); (b) **operand=instrument** (person walks herself); (c) **one-to-one with complex operand** (amplifier → passenger emergency card — one instrument per process, but coupled attributes of same operand); (d) **one-to-one with multiple operands** (circulatory system — heart/lung/capillaries each map 1:1, but operands include both oxygen-rich and oxygen-poor blood); (e) **one-to-many** (cook stirs AND cuts — one instrument, two processes); (f) **many-to-many** (food prep in kitchen AND dining room — many instruments, many processes).
-- **Form-to-process procedure** (line 2658): identify all form elements → identify all internal processes+operands → for each process, ask which form is needed → map form-to-process → reason about unassigned form.
-- **Structure-to-interaction rule** (line 2690): functional interaction usually requires a connection of form; some interactions (gravity, electromagnetic, ballistic) don't.
-- **Architectural layers** (§6.3, line 2757): value-operands → value-processes → value-instruments → supporting processes → supporting instruments. Non-idealities (seals, O-rings, covers) manage operands (contain, move, store) or improve performance/robustness.
-- **Interface specification** (Figure 6.11, line 2777): every interface has (a) common operand passing through boundary, (b) shared/common process of passing, (c) two compatible interface instruments — either **androgynous** (identical form on both sides) or **compatible** (different but fit together).
-- **Supporting layers** (§6.3, line 2751): every value instrument requires support (mechanical, power, thermal, HR for human organizations, IT for info systems) — OSI 7-layer / Internet 4-layer as classic examples where all value is in the application layer and the rest are support.
-
-### Patcher-ready seed (200–500 words)
-Ch 6 is the hinge chapter: architecture is the **mapping** of function to form, not an independent thing. Box 6.1 names five load-bearing terms: function, form, relationship, context (all from Chs 2–5), and concept (Ch 7). The Principle of Value and Architecture (Box 6.2) gives the lean-manufacturing axiom: "form attracts cost; function emerges benefit," so "developing good architectures (desired function for minimal form) is nearly synonymous with the delivery of value." Ch 6 §6.2 enumerates the **non-1:1 mapping taxonomy** KB-5 and KB-7 depend on (Figure 6.5): (a) no explicit instrument — there must be one, find it; (b) operand-as-instrument — a person walks herself; (c) one-to-one with complex operand — each process has its own instrument but the operands are coupled attributes of the same object (amplifier); (d) one-to-one with multiple operands — circulatory system has heart/lung/capillaries each doing one thing, but the operands (oxygen-rich blood, oxygen-poor blood) are multi-state; (e) one-to-many — the cook both stirs and cuts; (f) many-to-many — food preparation happens in kitchen and dining room, serving in both. This taxonomy is the warrant for c1v's KB-7 to enumerate non-ideal interface patterns rather than enforce 1:1. Ch 6 §6.3 pushes further: **non-idealities** require additional instruments that don't appear in the idealized value pathway (seals, O-rings, error-detection codes in communications). These non-ideal instruments either (i) manage operands (contain, move, store), (ii) improve performance or robustness, or (iii) correct biases. Non-idealities sit close to the value pathway but not on it. **Supporting functions** sit one or two layers out — motors need power, organizations need HR and IT, software stacks need OSI-layer-style support infrastructure. Crawley models the architecture in **five layers** (line 2757): value-operands, value-processes, value-instruments, supporting-processes, supporting-instruments. Interfaces (§6.3, Figure 6.11) get a three-part spec every KB-7 interface entry must enforce: a common operand that crosses the boundary unchanged, a shared process of passing, and two compatible instruments — either **androgynous** (identical — e.g., an Ethernet jack on both ends) or **compatible** (different but fit — e.g., a power cable and socket). This is the lowest-level schema an interface specification can have and still be complete.
